# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: knowledge-distillation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:knowledge-distillation/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] In machine learning, **knowledge distillation** or **model distillation** is the process of transferring knowledge from a large model to a smaller one.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] While large models (such as very deep neural networks or ensembles of many models) have more knowledge capacity than small models, this capacity might not be fully utilized.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] It can be just as computationally expensive to evaluate a model even if it utilizes little of its knowledge capacity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Knowledge distillation transfers knowledge from a large model to a smaller one without loss of validity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] As smaller models are less expensive to evaluate, they can be deployed on less powerful hardware (such as a mobile device).
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] There is also a less common technique called *Reverse Knowledge Distillation*, where knowledge is transferred from a smaller model to a larger one.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Model distillation is not to be confused with model compression, which describes methods to decrease the size of a large model itself, without training a new model.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Model compression generally preserves the architecture and the nominal parameter count of the model, while decreasing the bits-per-parameter.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Knowledge distillation has been successfully used in several applications of machine learning such as object detection, acoustic models, and natural language processing.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Recently, it has also been introduced to graph neural networks applicable to non-grid data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Knowledge transfer from a large model to a small one somehow needs to teach the latter without loss of validity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] If both models are trained on the same data, the smaller model may have insufficient capacity to learn a concise knowledge representation compared to the large model.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] However, some information about a concise knowledge representation is encoded in the pseudolikelihoods assigned to its output: when a model correctly predicts a class, it assigns a large value to the output variable corresponding to such class, and smaller values to the other output variables.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The distribution of values among the outputs for a record provides information on how the large model represents knowledge.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] where t is the *temperature*, a parameter which is set to 1 for a standard softmax.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The softmax operator converts the logit values $z_{i}(\mathbf {x} )$ to pseudo-probabilities: higher temperature values generate softer distributions of pseudo-probabilities among the output classes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Knowledge distillation consists of training a smaller network, called the *distilled model*, on a data set called the *transfer set* which could correspond to the original training set or consist of new, possibly unlabeled data.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] In this context, a high temperature increases the entropy of the output, therefore providing more information to learn for the distilled model compared to hard targets, and at the same time reducing the variance of the gradient between different records, thus allowing a higher learning rate.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] where the component of the loss with respect to the large model is weighted by a factor of $t^{2}$ since, as the temperature increases, the gradient of the loss with respect to the model weights scales by a factor of ${\frac {1}{t^{2}}}$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Under the assumption that the logits have zero mean, it is possible to show that model compression is a special case of knowledge distillation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] where ${\hat {z}}_{i}$ are the logits of the large model.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Deleting a parameter means fixing the parameter to zero.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The "saliency" of a parameter $\theta$ is defined as ${\frac {1}{2}}(\partial _{\theta }^{2}L)\theta ^{2}$ , where L is the loss function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The second-derivative $\partial _{\theta }^{2}L$ can be computed by second-order backpropagation.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Thus, the saliency of a parameter approximates the increase in loss if that parameter is deleted.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] A related methodology was *model compression* or *pruning*, where a trained network is reduced in size.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] This was first done in 1965 by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Valentin Lapa in the USSR (1965).
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Their deep networks were trained layer by layer through regression analysis.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Superfluous hidden units were pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Other neural network compression methods include Biased Weight Decay and Optimal Brain Damage.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] An early example of neural network distillation was published by Jürgen Schmidhuber in 1991, in the field of recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The problem was sequence prediction for long sequences, i.e., deep learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] One of them (the *automatizer*) predicted the sequence, and another (the *chunker*) predicted the errors of the automatizer.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Simultaneously, the automatizer predicted the internal states of the chunker.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] After the automatizer manages to predict the chunker's internal states well, it would start fixing the errors, and soon the chunker is obsoleted, leaving just one RNN in the end.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The idea of using the output of one neural network to train another neural network was also studied as the teacher-student network configuration.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] In 1992, several papers studied the statistical mechanics of teacher-student configurations with committee machines or parity machines.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] The knowledge distillation preprint of Geoffrey Hinton et al.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] (2015) formulated the concept and showed some results achieved in the task of image classification.
[src:knowledge-distillation/knowledge-distillation] Knowledge distillation is also related to the concept of *behavioral cloning* discussed by Faraz Torabi et. al.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Compressed models enable deployment on resource-constrained devices such as smartphones, embedded systems, edge computing devices, and consumer electronics computers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Efficient inference is also valuable for large corporations that serve large model inference over an API, allowing them to reduce computational costs and improve response times for users.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Model compression is not to be confused with knowledge distillation, in which a smaller "student" model is *trained* to imitate the input-output behavior of a larger "teacher" model (as opposed to using the "teacher"'s trained parameters or the "teacher"'s training targets).
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Several techniques are employed for model compression.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Pruning sparsifies a large model by setting some parameters to exactly zero.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] This effectively reduces the number of parameters.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] This allows the use of sparse matrix operations, which are faster than dense matrix operations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Pruning criteria can be based on magnitudes of parameters, the statistical pattern of neural activations, Hessian values, etc.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Quantization reduces the numerical precision of weights and activations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] For example, instead of storing weights as 32-bit floating-point numbers, they can be represented using 8-bit integers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Low-precision parameters take up less space, and takes less compute to perform arithmetic with.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] It is also possible to quantize some parameters more aggressively than others, so for example, a less important parameter can have 8-bit precision while another, more important parameter, can have 16-bit precision.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Inference with such models requires mixed-precision arithmetic.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Quantized models can also be used during training (rather than after training).
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] PyTorch implements automatic mixed-precision (AMP), which performs autocasting, gradient scaling, and loss scaling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Weight matrices can be approximated by low-rank matrices.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Let W be a weight matrix of shape $m\times n$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] A low-rank approximation is $W\approx UV^{T}$ , where U and V are matrices of shapes $m\times k,n\times k$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] When k is small, this both reduces the number of parameters needed to represent W approximately, and accelerates matrix multiplication by W .
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Low-rank approximations can be found by singular value decomposition (SVD).
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] The choice of rank for each weight matrix is a hyperparameter, and jointly optimized as a mixed discrete-continuous optimization problem.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] The rank of weight matrices may also be pruned after training, taking into account the effect of activation functions like ReLU on the implicit rank of the weight matrices.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] Model compression may be decoupled from training, that is, a model is first trained without regard for how it might be compressed, then it is compressed.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] However, it may also be combined with training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] The "train big, then compress" method trains a large model for a small number of training steps (less than it would be if it were trained to convergence), then heavily compress the model.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] It is found that at the same compute budget, this method results in a better model than lightly compressed, small models.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] In Deep Compression, the compression has three steps.
[src:knowledge-distillation/model-compression] The SqueezeNet paper reported that Deep Compression achieved a compression ratio of 35 on AlexNet, and a ratio of ~10 on SqueezeNets.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] In deep learning, **pruning** is the practice of removing parameters from an existing artificial neural network.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] The goal of this process is to reduce the size (parameter count) of the neural network (and therefore the computational resources required to run it) whilst maintaining accuracy.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] This can be compared to the biological process of synaptic pruning which takes place in mammalian brains during development.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Rank the neurons according to their importance (assuming there is a clearly defined measure for "importance").
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Check a termination condition (to be determined by the user) to see whether to continue pruning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Most work on neural network pruning does not remove full neurons or layers (structured pruning).
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Instead, it focuses on removing the most insignificant weights (unstructured pruning), namely, setting their values to zero.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] This can either be done globally by comparing weights from all layers in the network or locally by comparing weights in each layer separately.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Different metrics can be used to measure the importance of each weight.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Weight magnitude as well as combinations of weight and gradient information are commonly used metrics.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Early work suggested also to change the values of non-pruned weights.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Pruning can be applied at three different stages: before training, during training, or after training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] When pruning is performed during or after training, additional fine-tuning epochs are typically required.
[src:knowledge-distillation/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Each approach involves different trade-offs between accuracy and computational cost.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The **softmax function,** also known as **softargmax** or **normalized exponential function**, converts a tuple of K real numbers into a probability distribution over K possible outcomes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions, and is used in multinomial logistic regression.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function takes as input a tuple z of K real numbers, and normalizes it into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities proportional to the exponentials of the input numbers.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] That is, prior to applying softmax, some tuple components could be negative, or greater than one; and might not sum to 1; but after applying softmax, each component will be in the interval $(0,1)$ , and the components will add up to 1, so that they can be interpreted as probabilities.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Furthermore, the larger input components will correspond to larger probabilities.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In words, the softmax applies the standard exponential function to each element $z_{i}$ of the input tuple $\mathbf {z}$ (consisting of K real numbers), and normalizes these values by dividing by the sum of all these exponentials.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The normalization ensures that the sum of the components of the output vector $\sigma (\mathbf {z} )$ is 1.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The term "softmax" derives from the amplifying effects of the exponential on any maxima in the input tuple.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] For example, the standard softmax of $(1,2,8)$ is approximately $(0.001,0.002,0.997)$ , which amounts to assigning almost all of the total unit weight in the result to the position of the tuple's maximal element (of 8).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In general, instead of e a different base b > 0 can be used.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] As above, if b > 1 then larger input components will result in larger output probabilities, and increasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the largest input values.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Conversely, if 0 < b < 1 then smaller input components will result in larger output probabilities, and decreasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the smallest input values.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] A value proportional to the reciprocal of β is sometimes referred to as the *temperature*: ${\textstyle \beta =1/kT}$ , where k is typically 1 or the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] A higher temperature results in a more uniform output distribution (i.e. with higher entropy; it is "more random"), while a lower temperature results in a sharper output distribution, with one value dominating.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In some fields, the base is fixed, corresponding to a fixed scale, while in others the parameter β (or T) is varied.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function is a multiple-variable generalization of the logistic function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The Softmax function is a smooth approximation to the arg max function: the function whose value is the *index* of a tuple's largest element.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Softmax is not a smooth maximum (that is, a smooth approximation to the maximum function).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The term "softmax" is also used for the closely related LogSumExp function, which is a smooth maximum.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] For this reason, some prefer the more accurate term "softargmax", though the term "softmax" is conventional in machine learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This section uses the term "softargmax" for clarity.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] For example, in this encoding $\operatorname {arg\,max} (1,5,10)=(0,0,1),$ since the third argument is the maximum.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This can be generalized to multiple arg max values (multiple equal $z_{i}$ being the maximum) by dividing the 1 between all max args; formally 1/k where k is the number of arguments assuming the maximum.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] With the last expression given in the introduction, softargmax is now a smooth approximation of arg max: as ⁠ $\beta \to \infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg max.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In fact, softargmax is continuous, but arg max is not continuous at the singular set where two coordinates are equal, while the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The reason it fails to converge uniformly is that for inputs where two coordinates are almost equal (and one is the maximum), the arg max is the index of one or the other, so a small change in input yields a large change in output.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] However, softargmax does converge compactly on the non-singular set.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Conversely, as ⁠ $\beta \to -\infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg min in the same way, where here the singular set is points with two arg *min* values.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] It is also the case that, for any fixed β, if one input ⁠ $z_{i}$ ⁠ is much larger than the others *relative* to the temperature, $T=1/\beta$ , the output is approximately the arg max.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function is used in various multiclass classification methods, such as multinomial logistic regression (also known as softmax regression), multiclass linear discriminant analysis, naive Bayes classifiers, and artificial neural networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The operation is equivalent to applying a linear operator defined by $\mathbf {w}$ to tuples $\mathbf {x}$ , thus transforming the original, probably highly-dimensional, input to vectors in a K-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The standard softmax function is often used in the final layer of a neural network-based classifier.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Such networks are commonly trained under a log loss (or cross-entropy) regime, giving a non-linear variant of multinomial logistic regression.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Here, the Kronecker delta is used for simplicity (cf. the derivative of a sigmoid function, being expressed via the function itself).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] To ensure stable numerical computations subtracting the maximum value from the input tuple is common.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This approach, while not altering the output or the derivative theoretically, enhances stability by directly controlling the maximum exponent value computed.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] If the function is scaled with the parameter $\beta$ , then these expressions must be multiplied by $\beta$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] See multinomial logit for a probability model which uses the softmax activation function.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In the field of reinforcement learning, a softmax function can be used to convert values into action probabilities.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] where the action value $q_{t}(a)$ corresponds to the expected reward of following action a and $\tau$ is called a temperature parameter (in allusion to statistical mechanics).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] For high temperatures ( $\tau \to \infty$ ), all actions have nearly the same probability and the lower the temperature, the more expected rewards affect the probability.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] For a low temperature ( $\tau \to 0^{+}$ ), the probability of the action with the highest expected reward tends to 1.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In neural network applications, the number K of possible outcomes is often large, e.g. in case of neural language models that predict the most likely outcome out of a vocabulary which might contain millions of possible words.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This can make the calculations for the softmax layer (i.e. the matrix multiplications to determine the $z_{i}$ , followed by the application of the softmax function itself) computationally expensive.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] What's more, the gradient descent backpropagation method for training such a neural network involves calculating the softmax for every training example, and the number of training examples can also become large.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The computational effort for the softmax became a major limiting factor in the development of larger neural language models, motivating various remedies to reduce training times.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Approaches that reorganize the softmax layer for more efficient calculation include the **hierarchical softmax** and the **differentiated softmax**.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The hierarchical softmax (introduced by Morin and Bengio in 2005) uses a binary tree structure where the outcomes (vocabulary words) are the leaves and the intermediate nodes are suitably selected "classes" of outcomes, forming latent variables.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The desired probability (softmax value) of a leaf (outcome) can then be calculated as the product of the probabilities of all nodes on the path from the root to that leaf.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Ideally, when the tree is balanced, this would reduce the computational complexity from $O(K)$ to $O(\log _{2}K)$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In practice, results depend on choosing a good strategy for clustering the outcomes into classes.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] A Huffman tree was used for this in Google's word2vec models (introduced in 2013) to achieve scalability.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] A second kind of remedies is based on approximating the softmax (during training) with modified loss functions that avoid the calculation of the full normalization factor.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] These include methods that restrict the normalization sum to a sample of outcomes (e.g.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The standard softmax is numerically unstable because of large exponentiations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Subtracting by it guarantees that the exponentiations result in at most 1, see translation invariance in the mathematical properties.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] It can be efficiently computed on a GPU cluster using the FlashAttention algorithm.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Along the main diagonal $(x,\,x,\,\dots ,\,x),$ softmax is just the uniform distribution on outputs, $(1/n,\dots ,1/n)$ : equal scores yield equal probabilities.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Geometrically, softmax is constant along diagonals: this is the dimension that is eliminated, and corresponds to the softmax output being independent of a translation in the input scores (a choice of 0 score).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] By contrast, softmax is not invariant under scaling.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The standard logistic function is the special case for a 1-dimensional axis in 2-dimensional space, say the *x*-axis in the (x, y) plane.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function was used in statistical mechanics as the Boltzmann distribution in the foundational paper Boltzmann (1868), formalized and popularized in the influential textbook Gibbs (1902).
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The use of the softmax in decision theory is credited to R.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Duncan Luce, who used the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives in rational choice theory to deduce the softmax in Luce's choice axiom for relative preferences.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] In machine learning, the term "softmax" is credited to John S.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The output has most of its weight where the "4" was in the original input.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This is what the function is normally used for: to highlight the largest values and suppress values which are significantly below the maximum value.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] But note: a change of *temperature* changes the output.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] This shows that high temperatures de-emphasize the maximum value.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] The softmax function generates probability predictions densely distributed over its support.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Other functions like sparsemax or α-entmax can be used when sparse probability predictions are desired.
[src:knowledge-distillation/softmax-function] Also the Gumbel-softmax reparametrization trick can be used when sampling from a discrete-discrete distribution needs to be mimicked in a differentiable manner.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:knowledge-distillation/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
